  <mads:note type="source">Smith's Dictionary of Greek and Roman Biography and Mythology, Vol 3, 1867, p. 292-3:
    "Philippus, of Thessalonica, an epigrammatic poet, who besides composing a large number of epigrams himself,
    compiled one of the ancient Greek Anthologies. The whole number of epigrams assigned to him in the Greek Anthology is 
    nearly ninety...."</mads:note>
  <mads:note type="source">Brill's New Pauly: "P. from Thessalonica Epigraphist in Rome 1st cent....
    Epigraphist and compiler of an anthology of epigrams, later than Meleager... . Some 80 poems have 
    been handed down, in which P. imitates other epigrammatists - either from his own 'garland' or from 
    that of Meleager.." Albiani, Maria Grazia (Bologna). Philippus." Brill's New Pauly. Antiquity volumes
    edited by: Hubert Cancik and
    Helmuth Schneider . Brill, 2010. Brill Online. Tufts University Library. 29 October 2010</mads:note>
